Hepatitis: when should you talk to your doctor?
Almost half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, but in Hungary, chronic liver diseases are mentioned among the first causes of death.
In Hungary, the number of hepatitis patients goes up to a hundred thousand, of which only 7000 are treated: the reason is that many patients do not know how to be infected.
The liver definition is the collective name of infectious liver diseases caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities between symptoms, typical are hepatitis and itteracy, but their pathogens and diseases differ from one another.
Hepatitis viruses spread in two main forms depending on the pathogen agent: hepatitis A and E through the food channel (e.g. water and infected foods), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and organic fluids (sperm, vaginal loss, saliva).
For those travelling it is useful to immunise against the A and B virus, against the C no vaccine exists.
The symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating infected foods, accompanied by general illness, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After they form yellow spots on the skin and on the white of the eyes, the faeces become clear and the dark urine, the healing takes place within two or three weeks.
A million people die every year worldwide for hepatitis B, the most serious variant of the disease, causing liver tumors and liver cirrhosis.
The main reason, according to the estimates, is that only one person in ten receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: if it is not treated it can cause liver cirrhosis and liver tumors.
Most of the infected people do not know that they have contracted the disease because the pathogens destroy the liver cells in a subtle way, in many cases the first symptoms occur 20-30 years later.
Therefore, it is very important to prevent and perform regular medical tests.
This disease is much more frequent than the average in three groups: those who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug addicts and tattoos.
In the world today, the number of people infected by chronic hepatitis C virus amounts to 200 million.
Since a routine laboratory test also reveals the disease, it is worth addressing the family doctor when you notice any symptoms of unknown origin.
Recognized in time the disease is curable, the virus can be eliminated from the body, so it stops the infectious power and can prevent the formation of tumors.
September 30 is the world's day of hepatitis, organized for the first time in 2004 worldwide by associations of patients.
The aim is to draw attention to viral chronic hepatitis, to the causes of its development and to the early recognition of the disease.
