According to a recent survey, religious faith works as a kind of analgesic that has made the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
Scientists at Oxford University have conducted an interesting experiment, examining how faith in God affects the feeling of pain, reported British Telegraph.
In the somewhat bizarre investigation, an electroshock was performed to 12 Catholic believers and to other atheists, while all who observed a painting depicting the Virgin Mary.
Based on the results, Catholic believers were able to reject much of the pain.
Thanks to the exploration technique of the human brain, it was discovered that Catholics were able to activate the part of the brain responsible for controlling the pain.
The test is the first of a series of research in which, in addition to academics, scientists, philosophers and theologians of the University also take part.
The test took place exactly like this: an instrument that emits discharges and passes the electroshock was connected to the left hand of the subject of the experiment.
The researchers asked the participants to focus on two paintings, the Virgin Mary painted in the 17th century by Sassoferrat and the Lady with Leonardo da Vinci hermelin painted in the 15th century.
The authors of the examination hoped that the image of the Virgin Mary originated a sort of religious status among the believers, while Leonardo's framework was chosen because it did not differ too much from the other and considered it to be a calming effect.
